    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Here are my findings, organized by your three questions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Exact Legal Text of GDPR Article 20 (from Official EUR-Lex Source)\n\n**Source:** EUR-Lex - Regulation (EU) 2016/679 (Official Journal of the European Union)\n**URL:** https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32016R0679\n\nThe exact text as published on EUR-Lex:\n\n> **Article 20**\n> **Right to data portability**\n>\n> 1\\. The data subject shall have the right to receive the personal data concerning him or her, which he or she has provided to a controller, in a structured, commonly used and machine-readable format and have the right to transmit those data to another controller without hindrance from the controller to which the personal data have been provided, where:\n>\n> (a) the processing is based on consent pursuant to point (a) of Article 6(1) or point (a) of Article 9(2) or on a contract pursuant to point (b) of Article 6(1); and\n>\n> (b) the processing is carried out by automated means.\n>\n> 2\\. In exercising his or her right to data portability pursuant to paragraph 1, the data subject shall have the right to have the personal data transmitted directly from one controller to another, where technically feasible.\n>\n> 3\\. The exercise of the right referred to in paragraph 1 of this Article shall be without prejudice to Article 17. That right shall not apply to processing necessary for the performance of a task carried out in the public interest or in the exercise of official authority vested in the controller.\n>\n> 4\\. The right referred to in paragraph 1 shall not adversely affect the rights and freedoms of others.\n\nA mirror with the identical text is available at: https://gdpr-info.eu/art-20-gdpr\n\n---\n\n## 2. ICO Guidance on \"Machine-Readable Format\" Under Article 20\n\n**Source:** ICO - Right to data portability\n**URL:** https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/individual-rights/individual-rights/right-to-data-portability\n\nThe ICO provides detailed definitions for each of the three statutory requirements (\"structured,\" \"commonly used,\" and \"machine-readable\"). Here are the exact quotes:\n\n### On \"structured\":\n> Structured data allows for easier transfer and increased usability.\n>\n> The Open Data Handbook defines 'structured data' as:\n> > 'data where the structural relation between elements is explicit in the way the data is stored on a computer disk.'\n>\n> This means that software must be able to extract specific elements of the data. An example of a structured format is a spreadsheet, where the data is organised into rows and columns, ie it is 'structured'. In practice, some of the personal data you process will already be in structured form.\n\n### On \"commonly used\":\n> This simply means that the format you choose must be widely-used and well-established.\n>\n> However, just because a format is 'commonly used' does not mean it is appropriate for data portability. You have to consider whether it is 'structured', and 'machine-readable' as well.\n\n### On \"machine-readable\":\n> The Open Data Handbook states that 'machine readable' data is:\n> > 'Data in a data format that can be automatically read and processed by a computer.'\n>\n> Furthermore, Regulation 2 of the Re-use of Public Sector Information Regulations 2015 defines 'machine-readable format' as:\n> > 'A file format structured so that software applications can easily identify, recognise and extract specific data, including individual statements of fact, and their internal structure.'\n>\n> Machine-readable data can be made directly available to applications that request that data over the web. This is undertaken by means of an application programming interface (\"API\").\n>\n> If you are able to implement such a system then you can facilitate data exchanges with individuals and respond to data portability requests in an easy manner.\n\n### On recommended formats:\n> Where no specific format is in common use within your industry or sector, you should provide personal data using open formats such as CSV, XML and JSON. You may also find that these formats are the easiest for you to use when answering data portability requests.\n\nThe ICO also states:\n> CSV, XML and JSON are three examples of structured, commonly used and machine-readable formats that are appropriate for data portability. However, this does not mean you are obliged to use them. Other formats exist that also meet the requirements of data portability.\n\n### On interoperability (from Recital 68, quoted by ICO):\n> 'Data controllers should be encouraged to develop interoperable formats that enable data portability.'\n\n### On technical compatibility:\n> The right to data portability does not create an obligation for you to adopt or maintain processing systems which are technically compatible with those of other organisations (UK GDPR Recital 68). However, you should take a reasonable approach, and this should not generally create a barrier to transmission.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Does GDPR Require APIs or Just Export in a Structured Format?\n\n**The short answer: GDPR does NOT mandate APIs. It requires export in a structured, commonly used, machine-readable format. APIs are one optional mechanism, not a requirement.**\n\nHere is the evidence from the sources:\n\n### From the ICO guidance:\n> Machine-readable data can be made directly available to applications that request that data over the web. This is undertaken by means of an application programming interface (\"API\").\n> **If you are able to implement such a system** then you can facilitate data exchanges with individuals and respond to data portability requests in an easy manner.\n\nThe ICO explicitly uses the conditional \"if you are able\" -- APIs are presented as a helpful option, not a mandate.\n\n### From Article 20(2) itself:\n> In exercising his or her right to data portability pursuant to paragraph 1, the data subject shall have the right to have the personal data transmitted directly from one controller to another, **where technically feasible**.\n\nThe qualifier \"where technically feasible\" means direct transmission (whether via API or other means) is conditional, not absolute.\n\n### From the ICO on providing data:\n> You can achieve this by either:\n> - directly transmitting the requested data to the individual; or\n> - providing access to an automated tool that allows the individual to extract the requested data themselves.\n>\n> This does not create an obligation for you to allow individuals more general and routine access to your systems -- only for the extraction of their data following a portability request.\n\n### From the EDPB Guidelines (WP242 rev.01):\nThe authoritative EDPB guidelines confirm the format requirement is \"structured, commonly used and machine-readable\" (e.g., CSV, JSON, XML), and that direct controller-to-controller transmission is subject to technical feasibility. The guidelines are available at: https://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/items/611233\n\n### Summary on APIs vs. Export:\n| Requirement | Mandated by GDPR? |\n|---|---|\n| Provide data in structured, commonly used, machine-readable format (e.g., CSV, JSON, XML) | **Yes** -- required by Art. 20(1) |\n| Direct controller-to-controller transmission | **Conditional** -- only \"where technically feasible\" (Art. 20(2)) |\n| APIs specifically | **No** -- APIs are one implementation method, not a legal requirement |\n| Interoperable formats | **Encouraged**, not required (Recital 68) |\n\n---\n\n### All Source URLs:\n\n1. **EUR-Lex (Official EU text):** https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A32016R0679\n2. **gdpr-info.eu (verified mirror of official text):** https://gdpr-info.eu/art-20-gdpr\n3. **ICO guidance on data portability:** https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/individual-rights/individual-rights/right-to-data-portability\n4. **EDPB Guidelines WP242 rev.01 on data portability:** https://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/items/611233",
      "timestamp": 1783290115285
    },
